                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Serve the Opponent or Help Yourself</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=1869"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=1869"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=4630">Patrick "Fiftytwo" Mathieson</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 4630 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Discusses the two main play stratagies - worsen the opponent or make your armies stronger.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">When building my decks, I decide how my overall strategy is going to work. I don&#146;t mean like force draining, winning battles, retrieving, etc. I mean as a whole. You have two options: Hurting the opponent&#146;s armies or supporting yours.<br>
<br>
---Serve the Opponent (AKA Big Hurt)---<br>
<br>
Serve the opponent up some pain, that is! This strategy is based on hurting the opponent, with as much pain as possible. Basically you build up your offense while sacrificing your defense.<br>
<br>
One of Big Hurt&#146;s main ideas is to battle a lot. It&#146;s usually the easiest way to take down the opponent. This means that Big Hurt decks will be main decks with, of course, destiny adders. It&#146;s the best way to surprise the opponent and turn what they thought to be a battle in their advantage to a grave mistake. Cards like Lone Pilot, Lone Warrior, Skywalkers, etc, fit into this description.<br>
<br>
Secondly, Big Hurt decks are speedy. They set up quick and run out into the open looking for trouble. A theme would be to be able to pull cards from the reserve deck. Cards like Imperial Arrest order are great for this theme, and, when combined with Mobilization Points, leads to the third theme of Big Hurt, massive force generation. Your great army needs force to build itself up, and to get important cards into hand.<br>
<br>
So, Big Hurt decks have the following characteristics:<br>
-Lots of battling<br>
-Speed<br>
-Huge force generation<br>
<br>
Some examples of Big Hurt decks are:<br>
-Bring Him Before Me<br>
-Rebel Strike Team<br>
-Ralltir Ops<br>
<br>
---Help Yourself (AKA Patience)---<br>
<br>
The second type of deck is almost the exact opposite. You&#146;re giving yourself bonuses to power while limiting your opponents choices and advantages. Lots of defense, and a little offense. Think of it as kind of hiding in the darkness, slowly building up your forces.<br>
<br>
As with most decks, big force generation is very important. That rule is followed here, but with a twist. Patience decks have those 2/0 or 1/0 locations that give you good generation and limiting the opponent&#146;s. Limiting the opponent&#146;s force is very important, and that rule must be followed strictly.<br>
<br>
Secondly, if the opponent gets no force, then how do you make sure he loses force, since your force draining is limited? Well, lightsabers are good to sit and drain at a location where the opponent can&#146;t stop your drains. Also include some 2/1 locations to get some small drains in. Effects like Search and Destroy that make the opponent lose force automatically work well to make the opponent lose force are good too.<br>
<br>
Once again, the theme is to limit what the opponent can do. Patience decks are full of effects and interrupts that block the opponent from doing certain things. Examples include Do, or Do Not and Rebel/Imperial Barrier. Also, any effects that give you extra bonuses, whether it be force draining or battle destinies, also fit in nicely.<br>
<br>
Finally, Patience decks also pack good surprises, such as reacting. Speeders and AT-STs are perfect examples, and can catch an inexperience opponent off-guard.<br>
<br>
In summary, Patience decks have the following characteristics:<br>
-Little force for the opponent<br>
-Force drain bonuses<br>
-Limiting the opponent&#146;s choices<br>
-Reacting<br>
<br>
Examples of Patience decks are:<br>
-MWYHL (the Patience champion!)<br>
-Endor/Perimeter Patrol<br>
-Speeder bikes, at-sts<br>
<br>
---------<br>
<br>
So, when you&#146;re going to make a new deck, think about which type of deck it is: Patience, or Big Hurt. You can have a deck somewhere in the middle, like TIGIH decks, but mostly it&#146;s either one of the other.<br>
<br>
Thanks for reading.<br>
<br>
Patrick &quot;FiftyTwo&quot; Mathieson </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=1869"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=1869"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=1869" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
